04595nam a22006615i 9780271064833DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20212014pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710648337 a10.1515/97802710648332doi  a(DE-B1597)583749  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPQ2021.H4bE5 2014 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a843/.52231 aPrévost, Abbé, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Greek Girl's Story /cAbbé Prévost. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b6 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tTh e Greek Girl's Story -- tAppendix 1 contemporary source texts for the greek girl's story -- tAppendix 2 life and works of the Abbé Prévost -- tNotes -- tWorks Consulted0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith The Greek Girl's Story, Alan Singerman presents the first reliable, stand-alone translation and critical edition of Abbé Prévost's 1740 literary masterpiece Histoire d'une Grecque moderne. The text of this new English translation is based on Singerman's 1990 French edition, which Jonathan Walsh called "arguably the most valuable critical edition" of Prévost's novel to date. This new edition also includes a complete critical apparatus comprising a substantial introduction, notes, appendixes, and bibliography, all significantly updated from the 1990 French edition, taking into account recent scholarship on this work and providing some additional reflection on the question of Orientalism.Prévost's roman à clef is based on a true story involving the French ambassador to the Ottoman Porte from 1699 to 1711. It is narrated from the ambassador's viewpoint and is a model of subjective, unreliable narration (long before Henry James). It is remarkably modern in its presentation of an enigmatic, ambiguous character, as the truth about the heroine can never be established with certainty. It is the story of the tormented relationship between the diplomat and a beautiful young Greek concubine, Théophé, whom he frees from a pasha's harem. While her benefactor becomes increasingly infatuated with her and bent on becoming her lover, the Greek girl becomes obsessed with the idea of becoming a virtuous and respected woman. Viewing the ambassador as a father figure, she condemns his quasi-incestuous passion and firmly rejects his repeated seduction attempts. Unable to possess the young woman or tolerate the thought that she might grant to someone else what she has refused him, the narrator subjects her behavior to minute scrutiny in an effort to catch her in an indiscretion. His investigations are fruitless, however, and Théophé, the victim of incessant persecution, simply dies, leaving all the questions about her behavior unanswered.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aFrench literaturey18th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aSgard, Jean.1 aSingerman, Alan J.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311074525240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271064833zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271064833423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271064833.jpg  a978-3-11-074525-2  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK